“There is no light,” says Vuyokazi Yvonne Mathebula. In June last year, she had to identify the brutally assaulted and decomposing body of her sister, Nonhle Gloria Aphane. Today, the alleged perpetrator – said to be a close relative – walks around free of repercussion. 



To Mathebula, it seems the police have moved on from her younger sister’s murder while it is still painfully present for her. “I’m experiencing flashbacks. I was telling my younger brother today that even last night I dreamt about my sister.” But rather than focusing on her own post-traumatic stress, Mathebula says conversations with her psychologist have been consumed by worry about what the alleged killer remaining free means for her safety and that of other women in the area. 



<img data-attachment-id="156694" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/justice-for-gender-based-violence-is-a-fairy-tale/gbv_various002/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002.jpg" data-orig-size="2362,1575" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;5&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D850&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;25 August 2021: Vuyokazi Yvonne Mathebula the elder sister of Nonhle Aphane with a picture of her late sister on her phone. Picture: Ihsaan Haffejee&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1629895738&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;42&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;1250&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.01&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="GBV_various002" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;25 August 2021: Vuyokazi Yvonne Mathebula the elder sister of Nonhle Aphane with a picture of her late sister on her phone. Picture: Ihsaan Haffejee&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-156694" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various002-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />25 August 2021: Vuyokazi Mathebula shows a picture of her sister on her phone. (Photograph by Ihsaan Haffejee)



Any trust Mathebula once had in the police has dissolved. The burden is on her to phone every two weeks to follow up on the case, and even then “the police aren’t hearing us out”. She seeks not only justice but the closure that would come with the long overdue arrest of her sister’s killer. “I’m not free.”  



“Gender-based violence is happening each and every day, every hour, every minute,” says Mathebula, sighing in resignation but also anger. Statistics support her view. An estimated one in seven women globally experienced physical and/or sexual violence at the hands of a partner or husband in 2018. And women in South Africa are five times more likely to be murdered by an intimate partner than anywhere else in the world.



Good cop, bad cop



Mathebula is “scared of the very same police”, and she is not alone in her fear and distrust. An October 2021 survey found that 73% of South Africans distrust the police and spokesperson Javu Baloyi says the Commission for Gender Equality does not trust the police wholeheartedly either. Chief among his concerns is that “you can’t ask a woman to go and serve a protection order to the person who’s abusing her”. 



Tembisa Hospital nurse Lebogang Monene was shot six times in broad daylight by her police officer partner. It is a well-established reality that police officers feature disproportionately among those who kill their female partners. 



The commission is critical of relying solely on gender-based violence statistics because it is typical for the crime to go unreported. Women are told to “just report” their abusers, but a big reason for under-reporting is a fear that the police won’t take allegations seriously or that they will respond with a “negative, demeaning and discriminatory” attitude or a “lack of sensitivity”. To report a case to the police and expect results is “a fairy tale”, says Mathebula.



<img data-attachment-id="156704" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/justice-for-gender-based-violence-is-a-fairy-tale/gbv_various008/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008.jpg" data-orig-size="2362,1575" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;7.1&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Gopolang Ledwaba&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Canon EOS 5D Mark II&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;22 March 2022: Sometimes during the day people who stay at the shelter gather together to play game cards which is one of the games they enjoy playing when they&#039;re free from other duties.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1647962700&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;24&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;320&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.01&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="GBV_various008" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;22 March 2022: Sometimes during the day people who stay at the shelter gather together to play game cards which is one of the games they enjoy playing when they&#8217;re free from other duties.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-156704" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various008-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />22 March 2022: MES Impilo residents play cards during their downtime. (Photographs by Gopolang Ledwaba)



When young researchers posing as women attempting to escape an unsafe home environment tested this by calling every police station in Mpumalanga, KwaZulu-Natal and the Western Cape, the results revealed the magnitude of the problem. Only one in four stations was able to refer them to a shelter or social services office in the area, and three in four were asked “What is a shelter?”, “Well, why were you beaten?” or told “You don’t sound very sure whether you were abused or not”. When one of the callers explained that she was scared of her partner and did not want the police to come to her house, the officer told her “there is nothing more we can do to help” and hung up the phone. 



Mathebula hoped that because the police were there on the day of her sister’s murder, “the case would be treated with the urgency it deserves. Unfortunately it never happened like that.” Mathebula had gone nine months without seeing the inside of a courtroom at the time of publishing. And the Nelspruit magistrate’s court had a backlog of more than 200 gender-based violence cases. 



More than a shelter



MES Impilo, a shelter in Johannesburg, has had a more optimistic experience. Unit care manager Nonhlanhla Zulu says the police have been instrumental in helping the shelter expand its mandate. Originally for homeless people, it now takes in victims of domestic violence as well. “They are mainly brought in via the police,” says Zulu. 



The shelter has outreach programmes in shack settlements and other “places where poverty is too high”, say Zulu and fundraising and marketing manager Zama Ndlovu. This is in keeping with an understanding of the geography of violence and the connection between deprivation, high levels of crime and gender-based violence.  



Those who arrive at the shelter are met by a social worker and assessed before getting into the rhythm of morning workouts, shared meals, fiercely contested games of cards and – most importantly, say the MES staff – life skills classes. Ultimately, the shelter aims to reintegrate its residents into society safely and with a sense of empowerment. “We are training them to leave with a skill, to take personal responsibility for their lives,” says Zulu.




<img data-attachment-id="156699" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/justice-for-gender-based-violence-is-a-fairy-tale/gbv_various003-2/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1.jpg" data-orig-size="2362,1575" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Gopolang Ledwaba&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Canon EOS 5D Mark II&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;22 March 2022: A bedroom that is shared by females at MES Impilo. Only a minimum of two people can share and occupy a bedroom.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1647958559&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;24&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;640&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.00625&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="GBV_various003" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" data-id="156699"  src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-156699" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various003-1-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/G