<img data-attachment-id="156700" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/justice-for-gender-based-violence-is-a-fairy-tale/gbv_various004/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004.jpg" data-orig-size="2362,1575" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Gopolang Ledwaba&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Canon EOS 5D Mark II&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;22 March 2022: Dining area used by people who are staying at MES Impilo. The space is also used for fitness programme.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1647959051&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;24&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;1250&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.01&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="GBV_various004" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" data-id="156700"  src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-156700" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various004-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />
Left: 22 March 2022: A shared room in the women’s wing at the MES Impilo shelter in Johannesburg. Right: 22 March 2022: The dining area is also used for fitness programmes.



Ntokozo Nyati and Lungi Nzuza belong to the four-member team that runs a sewing business under MES Impilo. They first laid their hands on a sewing machine during the Outreach Foundation’s skills development programme in Hillbrow, to which MES is connected, and sewing has become far more than just a neat skill to have. “We use it to make a living.” Nyati is a mother of five and Nzuza has two boys. 



Nyati is putting the finishing touches to a chef’s jacket for a client. The vibrant colours and eye-catching patterns of garments, blankets, bedding, aprons, bags and hats lift the darkness of the room in which they work. When not sewing, they’re selling on the streets or at the Sunday market in Rosebank, or marketing their business on social media. “It doesn’t matter how beautiful the clothes are, if you don’t have clients it’s meaningless.”



Stories such Nyati and Nzuza’s are what researcher Lisa Vetten sees as part of a more complex picture of how shelters curb gender-based violence. They act as “an illustration of the folly of trying to draw a bright shining line between what is prevention and what is response”. Not only do shelters give survivors a way to earn an income, they also actively prevent violence. Refuge in a shelter means a woman doesn’t have to return to an abusive environment, nor are her children exposed to violence at a tender and impressionable age. Self-harm is also often prevented through access to psychological help. 



<img data-attachment-id="156706" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/justice-for-gender-based-violence-is-a-fairy-tale/gbv_various005-1/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1.jpg" data-orig-size="2362,1575" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;3.2&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Gopolang Ledwaba&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Canon EOS 5D Mark II&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;22 March 2022: Zama Ndlovu, 42 is a fundraising and marketing manager at MES Impilo.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1647963870&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;50&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;125&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.01&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="GBV_various005-1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;22 March 2022: Zama Ndlovu, 42 is a fundraising and marketing manager at MES Impilo.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-156706" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/GBV_various005-1-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />5. 22 March 2022: MES Impilo fundraising and marketing manager Zama Ndlovu.



The work of many hands 



Funding for shelters remains “deeply fraught with challenges”, which impedes their ability to provide the level of care they’d like to despite often being the only option for victims. Structured support and other avenues beyond shelters need reinforcement. The Commission for Gender Equality points to ways of reporting abuse without the knowledge of the perpetrator, such as its complaints line. 



Vetten says “family members, friends and communities are perhaps an underappreciated resource, because that kind of social solidarity should not be underestimated”. Any one of these people could significantly counteract the emotional abuse a victim is subjected to by affirming their fears and concerns, and communities can support victims by galvanising publicly against alleged abusers. This sense of solidarity extends to spaces like counselling and support groups, where women can share ways to safely escape toxic relationships. Vetten adds that registering as a shelter should be made easier for smaller and rural organisations, and for direct access to mental health support to be readily available at such shelters.  




